                    <desc>A translation of this text (and its commentary) is found in the Chinese Buddhist canon (Taishō 1620 and 1621, attributed to Dignāga) wherein the text’s title
            is rendered as 解捲論 (“Treatise of a Clenched Fist”). Thomas and Ui [1918] take the Tibetan title (lit. “Branches of the Parts”) to be a “free translation” of the Sanskrit and translate the
            Sanskrit title by taking vāla (√val) as “to roll” or “to twist” and hence hasta-vāla as “clenched fist” or “grasping with the hand,” noting that the text contains five verses symbolic of
            five fingers and a sixth summation verse symbolic of the act of closing them in grasping something. I have followed their line of reasoning in translating the title as well.</desc>
